------------------------------------------------------------------
THE CHALLENGE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We were given image_94a08a.png. The image looked completely
normal. A high-value stego challenge with no obvious clues.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 -- EXIF ANALYSIS
------------------------------------------------------------------

When an image looks clean and visual analysis reveals nothing,
metadata is the next stop. exiftool reads every metadata field
stored inside a file.

    exiftool image_94a08a.png

Most fields were standard. But the Custom Artist field contained
a massive amount of data -- far more than any legitimate artist
field would ever hold.

Remember: legitimate EXIF fields like Artist, Author, and
Comment are short strings. If any field contains hundreds or
thousands of characters, that is the hiding spot. exiftool
prints all fields in one pass -- scroll through the full output
and look for anything that seems disproportionately large.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 -- EXTRACT THE ANOMALOUS DATA
------------------------------------------------------------------

We copied the full contents of the Custom Artist field. The data
was a long hexadecimal string -- recognisable because it only
contained the characters 0-9 and a-f.

We saved it to a file for processing:

    echo "4b756253545..." > hex_data.txt

Remember: hex-encoded data in metadata is easy to spot because
it only uses the characters 0123456789abcdef and its length is
always even. If you see a massive field with only those
characters, it is hex-encoded binary data. Convert it and see
what file comes out.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 3 -- CONVERT HEX TO FILE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We converted the hex string back to its original binary form:

    xxd -r -p hex_data.txt output_file

Then checked what it was:

    file output_file

It came back as a plain text file. We read it:

    cat output_file

The flag was inside in plaintext.

Remember: xxd -r -p reverses a plain hex dump (no offsets, no
ASCII column) back into binary. This is the standard one-liner
for converting raw hex strings to files. After conversion always
run file on the result -- the recovered data could be a txt, a
zip, an image, or anything else, and you need to know before
you try to read it.

------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL COMMAND SEQUENCE
------------------------------------------------------------------

    exiftool image_94a08a.png
    -> Copy Custom Artist field contents to hex_data.txt
    xxd -r -p hex_data.txt output_file
    file output_file
    cat output_file

